\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Truth Tables
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "3_t_2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So by re-writing those truth tables we have got the following equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Output=S_{1}\,.\,\bar{S_{0}}\label{eq:3_1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}^{'}=\bar{S_{1}}S_{0}w+S_{1}\bar{S_{0}}w
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{0}^{'}=\bar{S_{1}}\bar{S_{0}}w
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, by implementing those formulas into a synchronized logic circuit, we
 have got the Moore machine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Level Converter Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To convert the voltage levels on the PCB for compatibility, we decided to
 use 2N7000 Mosfet Transistor.
 We used it to implement an inverter with Open-Collector.
 By connecting the output to a pull-up network with the voltage we want,
 we can convert the level with no problems, form 5(v) to 3.3(v), and vice
 versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Pull-Up network, we decided to use a resistor 
\begin_inset Formula $R=1\,(k\Omega)$
\end_inset

 so that when it's conected to ground, te current flowing through the inverter
 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $10\,(mA)$
\end_inset

, and when the inverter produces a High Z, the resistor its not enough big
 to produce a High Z to the output, and set the output to a logic 1.
\end_layout

